<p>Bellevue's cold climate requires robust heating systems capable of maintaining comfort during harsh Nebraska winters, where temperatures can drop well below freezing for extended periods. For optimal performance in this climate, homeowners should consider high-efficiency furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher, paired with central air conditioning systems rated at minimum 16 SEER for cooling efficiency. Heat pump systems can work in Bellevue but require cold-climate models or hybrid systems that switch to backup heating when temperatures drop below 25¬∞F, which occurs frequently during winter months.</p>

<p>The most popular HVAC solutions for Bellevue's 1,820 square foot average homes include variable-speed gas furnaces paired with high-efficiency air conditioners, providing year-round comfort with lower operating costs. Ductless mini-split systems are gaining popularity for additions and specific zones, offering SEER ratings up to 25+ for cooling and HSPF ratings of 10+ for heating. When combined with solar panel systems, homeowners can achieve significant energy independence, especially during shoulder seasons when heating and cooling demands are moderate and solar production is strong.</p>

<h2>Bellevue Energy Incentives</h2>
<p>Bellevue residents have access to several attractive incentives that make solar and HVAC upgrades more affordable. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit on total system costs through 2032, then stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. Nebraska offers additional state-level incentives, including property tax exemptions for solar installations, meaning the added home value from solar panels won't increase property taxes. The state also provides sales tax exemptions on solar equipment purchases, saving homeowners an additional 5.5% on system costs.</p>

